  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Living Expression'
      title: The Living Expression
      number: 1
      content: 'In the beginning [[COMMENT(0)]] the Living Expression  was already
        there.And the Living Expression was with God, yet fully God. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:1
        content: "  Most scholars consider the first eighteen verses of John to be
          the words of an ancient hymn or poem that was cherished by first-century
          believers in Christ.      The Greek is  , which has a rich and varied background
          in both Greek philosophy and Judaism. The Greeks equated    with the highest
          principle of cosmic order. God\u2019s    in the Old Testament conveys his
          powerful self-expression in creation, revelation, and redemption. In the
          New Testament we have this new unique view of God given to us by John,
          which signifies the presence of God himself in the flesh. Some have translated
          this rich term as \u201CWord.\u201D Though the Greek term    may be rendered
          \u201Cword,\u201D it would be wrong to think it indicates primarily a lexical
          unit in a sentence.    is more accurately understood as a form of self-revealing
          or \u201Cmessage.\u201D Jesus Christ is the eternal Message, the creative
          Word, and the Living Expression of God made visible. He is the divine self-expression
          of all that God is, contains, and reveals in incarnated flesh. Just as
          we express ourselves in words, God has perfectly expressed himself in Christ.
          Jesus is God\u2019s Story.      The Living Expression (Christ) fully possesses
          every attribute of deity held by God the Father (). The Living Expression
          existed eternally as a separate individual but essentially the same, as
          one with the Father.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "They were together\u2014face-to-face, [[COMMENT(0)]] in the very
        beginning. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:2
        content: "  The Greek word used here and the Hebraic concept conveyed is
          that of being before God\u2019s face. There is no Hebrew word for \u201Cpresence\u201D
          (i.e., the \u201Cpresence\u201D of God), only the word \u201Cface.\u201D     
          Both    and    speak of  . In Genesis Moses spoke of the beginning of time,
          but John speaks of eternity past, a beginning before time existed. The
          Living Expression is Christ who existed eternally as part of the Trinity.
          He has no beginning, being one with the Father.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: And through his creative inspirationthis Living Expression made all
        things, [[COMMENT(0)]]for nothing has existence apart from him!
      comments:
      - number: 1:3
        content: "  Or \u201Call things happened because of him and nothing happened
          apart from him.\u201D The Aramaic is \u201Ceverything was in his hand\u201D
          (of power). See  ;  .    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'A fountain of life was in him, [[COMMENT(0)]]for his life is light
        for all humanity. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:4
        content: "  See  . The Aramaic reads \u201CIn him were lives\u201D (plural)\u2014not
          only multiple human lives, but also spiritual life, eternal life, and life
          in every form. John used the word    () thirty-seven times in his gospel.     
          Jesus Christ brings the light of eternal life and the full revelation of
          God (). The Gospel of John is easily divided into three sections: life
          (chs.  ), light (chs.  ), and love (chs.  ).    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "And this Light never fails to shine through darkness\u2014Light that
        darkness could not overcome! [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:5
        content: '  The Greek has a double meaning here. (1) Darkness could not diminish
          this Light, nor could it comprehend it. (2) The darkness can also be a
          metaphor for the sons of darkness.    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: Suddenly a man appeared who was sent from God,a messenger named John.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 1:6
        content: '  This is John, the Baptizer. See  .    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: For he came as a witness, to point the way to the Light of Life,and
        to help everyone believe.
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: John was not that Light but he came to show who is.For he was merely
        a messenger to speak the truth about the Light.
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'For the perfect Light of Truth [[COMMENT(0)]] was coming into the
        worldand shine upon everyone. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe True [Genuine, Perfect] Light.\u201D      Or \u201Cto
          enlighten everyone.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: He entered into the world he created,yet the world was unaware. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 1:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe world [of humanity] didn\u2019t perceive it.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "He came to the people he created [[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014to those who
        should have received him,but they did not recognize him."
      comments:
      - number: 1:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cto his own\u201D (things or people).    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: But those who embraced him and took hold of his name [[COMMENT(0)]]he
        gave authority to becomethe children of God!
      comments:
      - number: 1:12
        content: "  Or \u201Cthose who are putting faith into his name.\u201D To
          \u201Clay hold of his name\u201D means to believe everything he represents
          and put into practice what he taught in the power of his name.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "He was not born by the joining of human parents [[COMMENT(0)]]or
        from natural means,  or by a man\u2019s desire,but he was born of God. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cnot from streams of blood\u201D (i.e., the blood of
          a father and mother). Although many translations connect this verse with
          the children of God (v.  ), the old Latin translation as well as two church
          fathers, Irenaeus and Tertullian, argue that it is John\u2019s reference
          to the virgin birth of Christ (also v.  ).      Or \u201Cfrom the natural
          realm.\u201D      Or \u201Cborn out from God.\u201D The Living Expression
          (message) is now \u201Chumanized\u201D (and become the messenger). However,
          the vast majority of translations and expositors see here not Jesus\u2019
          virgin birth, but the new birth of those who became \u201Cchildren of God\u201D
          in v.  . Both are clearly presented in the Scriptures.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: And so the Living Expressionbecame a man [[COMMENT(0)]] and lived
        among us! We gazed upon his glory, the glory of the One and Only who came
        from the Father overflowingwith tender mercy  and truth!
      comments:
      - number: 1:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cbecame visible.\u201D      Or \u201Clive within us.\u201D
          This is the fulfillment of  . The \u201CGod with us\u201D is Jesus Christ
          our Immanuel. He is    in that he is in human form, and is still in human
          form within the Trinity eternally. The Greek and Aramaic can be translated
          \u201Che pitched his tent among us.\u201D John\u2019s wording takes us
          back into the book of Exodus where: (1) God came down and lived in the
          tent (tabernacle) in the wilderness (). (2) God revealed his glory in the
          pillar of fire and cloud (). (3) God identified himself as the One and
          Only (\u201CI am Yahweh your God&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. You may have no gods
          other than me,\u201D [;  ]). (4) God proclaimed his wrap-around love ().     
          The Aramaic is \u201CWe gazed upon his preciousness.\u201D John gazed upon
          Jesus\u2019 unveiled glory on the Mount of Transfiguration ().      The
          Aramaic is \u201CUnique and Beloved Son.\u201D The Greek word,  , means
          \u201Cof a single [] kind [].\u201D This word is also used for Isaac in   
          as Abraham\u2019s uniquely precious son, but not his only one.      The
          Aramaic word,  , means \u201Cloving kindness or goodness.\u201D The Greek
          word is  , which can also be translated, \u201Cgrace, favor, sweetness,
          pleasure or delight.\u201D This translation has combined all those concepts
          in the words  . Truly, Jesus Christ is full of everything that our hearts
          crave.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "John announced the truth about himwhen he taught the people,\u201CHe\u2019s
        the One!He\u2019s the One I\u2019ve been telling you would come after me,even
        though he ranks far above me,because he existed before I was even born.\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:15
        content: "  This reveals the eternal nature of Jesus Christ, for John was
          older than Jesus. The Aramaic can be translated \u201CHe is preferred before
          me, for he has priority over me.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'And from the overflow of his fullnesswe received [[COMMENT(0)]] grace
        heaped upon more grace! '
      comments:
      - number: 1:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cout of his fullness we are fulfilled\u201D (Aramaic).
          That is, every believer receives from the fullness of Christ a divine completeness.
          We are given from him whatever each requires for the perfection of his
          character and for the fulfillment of his life\u2019s purpose. See  ;  ; 
          .      Or \u201Cone gracious gift after another.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: Moses gave us the Law, but Jesus, the Anointed One,unveils truth wrapped
        in tender mercy. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 1:17
        content: '  Moses was the lawgiver, Jesus is the grace-giver. In the first
          miracle of Moses, he turned water into blood, resulting in death. In the
          first miracle of grace, Jesus turned water into wine, resulting in life
          and celebration.    '
    - name: '18: The Ministry of John the Baptizer'
      title: The Ministry of John the Baptizer
      number: 18
      content: No one ever before gazed upon the full splendor of Godexcept his uniquely
        beloved Son,who is cherished by the Father [[COMMENT(0)]]and held close to
        his heart.Now that he has come to us, he has unfolded the full explanation
        of who God truly is!
      comments:
      - number: 1:18
        content: "  Or \u201Cfrom the lap of the Father.\u201D This is an idiom for
          the place of closest intimacy.      Or \u201CHe has led the way into the
          knowledge of God.\u201D The Greek word,  , can mean either \u201Cto lead
          the way\u201D or \u201Cto explain.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Now this was John\u2019s testimony when some of the Jewish leaders
        [[COMMENT(0)]] sent an entourage of priests and temple servants  from Jerusalem
        to interrogate him. \u201CWho are you?\u201D they asked him."
      comments:
      - number: 1:19
        content: "  Or simply, \u201CJews,\u201D a metonymy for \u201CJewish leaders.\u201D
          Obviously, not all Jews opposed John\u2019s ministry. Some estimate that
          John and his disciples baptized as many as one million people. It is possible
          that John was a part of the Essene community of devout Jews.      Or \u201CLevites.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "John answered them directly, saying, \u201CI am not the Messiah!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CThen who are you?\u201D they asked. \u201CAre you Elijah?\u201D\u201CNo,\u201D
        John replied.So they pressed him further, \u201CAre you the prophet Moses
        said was coming, the one we\u2019re expecting?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CNo,\u201D
        he replied."
      comments:
      - number: 1:21
        content: "  See  . In    Jesus is identified as that \u201CProphet.\u201D    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CThen who are you?\u201D they demanded. \u201CWe need an answer
        for those who sent us. Tell us something about yourself\u2014anything!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "John answered them, \u201CI am an urgent, thunderous voice crying
        out in the desert\u2014clear the way and prepare your hearts for the coming
        of the Lord Yahweh!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:23
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. See  . The Aramaic is clear that
          the preparations are for the Lord Yahweh, signifying the deity of Jesus
          Christ. The Greek is \u201CMake straight the way for the Lord [].\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Then some members of the religious sect known as the Pharisees [[COMMENT(0)]]
        questioned John, '
      comments:
      - number: 1:24
        content: "  Or \u201Cseparated ones.\u201D They were the religious leaders
          of the day who considered themselves separated from sin and closer to God
          than other people.    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CWhy do you baptize the people if you are neither the Messiah,
        Elijah, nor the Prophet?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '26-27: '
      title: 
      number: 26-27
      content: "John answered them, \u201CI baptize the people in this river, but
        the One who will take my place is to be more honored than I, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        but even when he stands among you, you will not recognize or embrace him!
        I am not worthy enough to stoop down in front of him and untie his sandals!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: "1:26\u201327"
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '26-27: '
      title: 
      number: 26-27
      content: "John answered them, \u201CI baptize the people in this river, but
        the One who will take my place is to be more honored than I, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        but even when he stands among you, you will not recognize or embrace him!
        I am not worthy enough to stoop down in front of him and untie his sandals!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: "1:26\u201327"
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '28: The Lamb of God'
      title: The Lamb of God
      number: 28
      content: 'All these events took place at Bethany, [[COMMENT(0)]] where John
        was baptizing at the place of the crossing of the Jordan River. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:28
        content: "  This was a different Bethany than the one near Jerusalem, commonly
          referred to in the Gospels. Some Greek manuscripts have the location as
          \u201CBethabara,\u201D however, the Aramaic is clearly Bethany.      As
          translated from the Aramaic. This place of crossing is likely where the
          children of Israel crossed into the promised land when the Jordan River
          parted and they passed through on dry land. See  . This place is a powerful
          reminder of crossing over into a new day, a new era for Israel. God chose
          this place for John to baptize.    "
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "The very next day, John saw Jesus coming to him to be baptized, and
        John cried out, \u201CLook! There he is\u2014God\u2019s Lamb! [[COMMENT(0)]]
        He takes away  the sin of the entire world!   "
      comments:
      - number: 1:29
        content: "  Jesus was publicly washed as the Lamb of God and proven to be
          without flaw or blemish, ready to become the sacrifice for all the world.
          Although he will become the Lion of the tribe of Judah in resurrection
          power, John points to him as the meek Lamb, a willing sacrifice for our
          sins.      Or \u201Clift off\u201D (the burden). The Greek word used here
          is often used for \u201Clifting up and away\u201D an anchor from off the
          ocean floor.      The Aramaic is \u201Cthe sins of the universe.\u201D
          To take away our sins is a figure of speech that means \u201Che will break
          sin\u2019s grip from humanity, taking away both its guilt and power from
          those who believe.\u201D    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'I told you that a Mighty One [[COMMENT(0)]] would come who is far
        greater than I am, because he existed long before I was born! '
      comments:
      - number: 1:30
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "My baptism was for the preparation of his appearing to Israel, even
        though I didn\u2019t recognize him.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "Then, as he baptized Jesus, he proclaimed these words: \u201CI see
        the Spirit of God appear like a dove descending from the heavenly realm and
        landing upon him\u2014and it remained on him! [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:32
        content: "  Jesus, the Lamb, took away our sins, and the Holy Spirit, the
          Dove, brings to man the life of God. Jesus didn\u2019t come to start a
          movement but to bring the fullness of life to us. This \u201CDove\u201D
          points to the dove that Noah released from the ark. It found no place to
          rest in a fallen world. The final time Noah released the dove it flew and
          never returned. It flew throughout history over Abraham and the patriarchs,
          over the prophets and kings, finding no place to rest, until at last, there
          was a heavenly man who carried the life of heaven\u2014upon him the dove
          (Holy Spirit) rested and remained. There was nothing that could offend
          heaven in the life of our Lord Jesus.    "
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Before this I didn\u2019t know who he was. But the one who sent me
        to baptize with water had told me, \u2018You will see the Spirit come down
        and stay on someone. He will be the One I have sent to baptize with the Holy
        Spirit.\u2019 [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:33
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Spirit of Holiness.\u201D    "
    - name: "34: Jesus\u2019 First Followers"
      title: "Jesus\u2019 First Followers"
      number: 34
      content: "Now I have seen this happen and I can tell you for sure that this
        man is the Son of God.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:34
        content: "  Some Greek manuscripts have \u201Cthe Chosen One of God.\u201D
          The Aramaic is clearly \u201Cthe Son of Elohim.\u201D    "
    - name: '35-36: '
      title: 
      number: 35-36
      content: "The next day, Jesus walked right past where John and two of his disciples
        were standing. John, gazing upon Jesus, pointed to him and prophesied, \u201CLook!
        There\u2019s God\u2019s sacrificial  [[COMMENT(0)]] Lamb!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: "1:35\u201336"
        content: "  To the Western gentile in the twenty-first century, the phrase
          \u201CLamb of God\u201D evokes a fluffy pet. To John and his disciples,
          lambs were for sacrifice.    "
    - name: '35-36: '
      title: 
      number: 35-36
      content: "The next day, Jesus walked right past where John and two of his disciples
        were standing. John, gazing upon Jesus, pointed to him and prophesied, \u201CLook!
        There\u2019s God\u2019s sacrificial  [[COMMENT(0)]] Lamb!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: "1:35\u201336"
        content: "  To the Western gentile in the twenty-first century, the phrase
          \u201CLamb of God\u201D evokes a fluffy pet. To John and his disciples,
          lambs were for sacrifice.    "
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "And as soon as John\u2019s two disciples heard this, they immediately
        left John and began to follow a short distance behind Jesus."
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Jesus turned around and saw they were following him and asked, <JESUS>\u201CWhat
        do you want?\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] They responded, \u201CRabbi (which
        means, Master Teacher ), where are you staying?\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 1:38
        content: "  This is the first recorded saying of Jesus in the Gospels. It
          is a question that every follower of Jesus should be asked: \u201CWhat
          do you want in following me?\u201D Do we want something only for ourselves?
          A ministry? Answers to prayer? Or do we simply want to be with him? Their
          answer, \u201CWhere are you staying?\u201D shows that they were seeking
          only him. The first question God asked Adam and Eve was, \u201CWhere are
          you?\u201D The first words of the God-man were, \u201CWhat do you want?\u201D     
          The parenthetical words are added by the author, John.    is an honorific
          term that means more than teacher. The Aramaic word is best translated
          \u201CMaster,\u201D or \u201CMaster Teacher.\u201D      Or \u201CWhere
          do you abide?\u201D This is the same word used in ch.    where it refers
          to life-union, to be joined to Jesus as the living vine. Jesus wants everyone
          to come and discover where he \u201Cabides\u201D in life-union with his
          Father. See  .    "
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "Jesus answered, <JESUS>\u201CCome and discover for yourselves.\u201D</JESUS>
        So they went with him and saw where he was staying, and since it was late
        in the afternoon, they spent the rest of the day with Jesus."
      comments: []
    - name: '40-41: '
      title: 
      number: 40-41
      content: "One of the two disciples who heard John\u2019s words and began to
        follow Jesus was a man named Andrew. [[COMMENT(0)]] He first found his brother,
        Simon Peter, and told him, \u201CWe have found the Anointed One!\u201D  (Which
        is translated, the Christ.) "
      comments:
      - number: "1:40\u201341"
        content: "    means \u201Cbrave.\u201D      Or \u201CMessiah.\u201D The word   
          is taken from the Hebrew verb, \u201Cto anoint with oil.\u201D In the Old
          Testament, both priests () and kings () were anointed. In the New Testament,
          Jesus is the Anointed One (;  ) to deliver, to save, and to reconcile us
          back to God.    "
    - name: '40-41: '
      title: 
      number: 40-41
      content: "One of the two disciples who heard John\u2019s words and began to
        follow Jesus was a man named Andrew. [[COMMENT(0)]] He first found his brother,
        Simon Peter, and told him, \u201CWe have found the Anointed One!\u201D  (Which
        is translated, the Christ.) "
      comments:
      - number: "1:40\u201341"
        content: "    means \u201Cbrave.\u201D      Or \u201CMessiah.\u201D The word   
          is taken from the Hebrew verb, \u201Cto anoint with oil.\u201D In the Old
          Testament, both priests () and kings () were anointed. In the New Testament,
          Jesus is the Anointed One (;  ) to deliver, to save, and to reconcile us
          back to God.    "
    - name: '42: Jesus Calls Philip and Nathanael'
      title: Jesus Calls Philip and Nathanael
      number: 42
      content: "Then Andrew brought Simon to meet Jesus. When he gazed upon Andrew\u2019s
        brother, he prophesied to him, <JESUS>\u201CYou are Simon and your father\u2019s
        name is John.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>But from now on, everyone will
        call you Cephas\u201D</JESUS> (which means, Peter the Rock). "
      comments:
      - number: 1:42
        content: "  The Aramaic can also be translated \u201CYou are Simon, son of
          the dove.\u201D Simon means \u201Cone who hears.\u201D      The Aramaic
          word is  , which means \u201Crock.\u201D It is anglicized as \u201CPeter.\u201D
          This parenthetical statement is not found in the Aramaic, but only in Greek
          manuscripts. It appears that the Greek text is admitting it is a translation
          from the Aramaic.    "
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: "The next day, Jesus decided to go to Galilee, where he found Philip.
        Jesus said to him, <JESUS>\u201CCome and follow me.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: '(Now Philip, Andrew, and Peter had all grown up together in the village
        of Bethsaida.) [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:44
        content: "  Bethsaida means \u201Cplace of fishing,\u201D and was a village
          on Lake Galilee.    "
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: "Philip went to look for his friend, Nathanael, [[COMMENT(0)]] and
        told him, \u201CWe\u2019ve found him! We\u2019ve found the One we\u2019ve
        been waiting for! It\u2019s Jesus, son of Joseph from Nazareth! He\u2019s
        the One whom Moses and the prophets prophesied would come!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 1:45
        content: "  Nathanael means \u201Cgift of God.\u201D Most scholars agree
          that he is the same one as the Bartholomew mentioned as one of Jesus\u2019
          apostles. Almost every time Philip\u2019s name is listed as an apostle,
          it is followed by Bartholomew.    "
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: "Nathanael sneered, \u201CNazareth! What good thing could ever come
        from Nazareth?\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] Philip answered, \u201CCome and let\u2019s
        find out!\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: 1:46
        content: "  Jesus and his disciples were Galileans and spoke the northern
          dialect of Aramaic. Galileans were considered somewhat backward. Isaiah
          called that region \u201Cthe land of the gentile peoples, those surrounded
          with great darkness.\u201D Yet this was the region where the Messiah\u2019s
          light would shine forth. See  ;  .    "
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "When Jesus saw Nathanael approaching, he said, <JESUS>\u201CHere
        comes a true son of Israel\u2014an honest man with no hidden motive!\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: "Nathanael was stunned and said, \u201CBut you\u2019ve never met me\u2014how
        do you know anything about me?\u201DJesus answered, <JESUS>\u201CNathanael,
        right before Philip came to you, I saw you sitting under the shade of a fig
        tree.\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:48
        content: "  Although we can only speculate what Nathanael was doing while
          sitting under the fig tree, it mattered very personally to him. Perhaps,
          he was confessing to God his love for him and his desire to be pure and
          holy. Or perhaps, he was meditating on the Scriptures that speak of the
          coming Messiah. A fig tree is often a biblical metaphor of God\u2019s purpose
          and destiny coming to fruitfulness, especially as it relates to establishing
          God\u2019s kingdom on the earth. See  ;  . Some scholars speculate that
          the phrase \u201CI saw you under the fig tree\u201D could be an Aramaic
          idiom for \u201CI knew you since you were in the cradle.\u201D Some Jewish
          scholars see the term \u201Cunder the fig tree\u201D as an ancient Jewish
          idiom that means studying the messianic prophecies. The idiom stems from 
          , in a passage describing the future messianic kingdom: \u201CEach of them
          will sit under their vine, and under their fig tree.\u201D    "
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "Nathanael blurted out, \u201CTeacher, you are truly the Son of God
        and the King of Israel!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: "Jesus answered, <JESUS>\u201CDo you believe simply because I told
        you I saw you sitting under a fig tree? You will experience even more impressive
        things than that!</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: "<JESUS>I prophesy to you eternal truth:</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>From now on,</JESUS>    <JESUS>you all will see</JESUS>    <JESUS>an
        open heaven and gaze upon the Son of Man</JESUS>    <JESUS>like a stairway
        reaching into the sky</JESUS>    <JESUS>with the messengers of God climbing
        up and down upon</JESUS>    <JESUS>him!\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 1:51
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. John records Jesus using this
          phrase twenty-five times. The Greek is \u201CAmen, amen I say to you.\u201D     
          As translated from the Aramaic.      Or \u201Cyou [plural] will spiritually
          see.\u201D This is a promise for every believer today.      \u201CSon of
          Man\u201D is a messianic term pointing to Christ, not as the son of   
          man, but the Son of Man (humanity). He is not Joseph\u2019s son, but the
          Son of God.      The \u201Cstairway into the sky\u201D is an obvious reference
          to \u201CJacob\u2019s Ladder\u201D as the fulfillment of his dream found
          in  . Jesus Christ is that stairway that joins earth to heaven and brings
          heaven to earth. The word for \u201Cangels\u201D can also be translated
          \u201Cmessengers\u201D and could be humans given access into the heavenly
          realm through the blood of Jesus. Jesus, as the stairway, was both in heaven
          and on earth as he spoke this to Nathanael. What mysteries surround him!     
          Or \u201Cnext to.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Jesus Comes to a Wedding'
      title: Jesus Comes to a Wedding
      number: 1
      content: "Now on the third day, [[COMMENT(0)]] Jesus\u2019 mother went to a
        wedding feast in the Galilean village of Cana.   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:1
        content: "  This was a Tuesday as counted by the Hebrew week beginning on
          Sunday. The \u201Cthird day\u201D was chosen as the wedding day in ancient
          Judaism because it is only on the third day of creation that God said \u201CIt
          was good\u201D twice (see  ,  ). Thus, the Jews considered the day twice
          blessed. Tuesdays were ideal for Jewish weddings, for that gave the guests
          time to get there after the Sabbath and remain for the multiple days of
          the wedding feast. The third day is also a picture of the day of resurrection
          glory, the day Jesus rose from the dead. This miracle is a revelation of
          moving from death to resurrection life, water to wine.      Cana means
          \u201Cland of reeds,\u201D which points to the weak and fragile nature
          of man. See  ;  ;  .    "
    - name: '2-3: '
      title: 
      number: 2-3
      content: "Jesus and his disciples were all invited to the banquet, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        but with so many guests, they ran out of wine.  And when Mary realized it,
        she came to Jesus and asked, \u201CThey have no wine; can\u2019t you do something
        about it?\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: "2:2\u20133"
        content: "  This wedding likely involved someone of Jesus\u2019 family since
          Mary and all his disciples were also in attendance. A Near Eastern wedding
          would often last between three and seven days.      Interpreting Mary\u2019s
          words for today we could say, \u201CReligion has failed, it has run out
          of wine.\u201D The traditions of religion cannot gladden the heart, but
          Jesus can (). Moses (the law) turned water into blood, but Jesus (grace)
          turned water into wine.      This is a dilemma that Mary is hoping Jesus
          will solve by performing a miracle. Mary had no doubt about the power and
          anointing of her Son. Running out of wine is a picture of how the joy of
          this world runs out and fades away.    "
    - name: '2-3: '
      title: 
      number: 2-3
      content: "Jesus and his disciples were all invited to the banquet, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        but with so many guests, they ran out of wine.  And when Mary realized it,
        she came to Jesus and asked, \u201CThey have no wine; can\u2019t you do something
        about it?\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: "2:2\u20133"
        content: "  This wedding likely involved someone of Jesus\u2019 family since
          Mary and all his disciples were also in attendance. A Near Eastern wedding
          would often last between three and seven days.      Interpreting Mary\u2019s
          words for today we could say, \u201CReligion has failed, it has run out
          of wine.\u201D The traditions of religion cannot gladden the heart, but
          Jesus can (). Moses (the law) turned water into blood, but Jesus (grace)
          turned water into wine.      This is a dilemma that Mary is hoping Jesus
          will solve by performing a miracle. Mary had no doubt about the power and
          anointing of her Son. Running out of wine is a picture of how the joy of
          this world runs out and fades away.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Jesus replied, <JESUS>\u201CMy dear one, don\u2019t you understand
        that if I do this, it will change nothing for you, but it will change everything
        for me!</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>My hour</JESUS>  <JESUS>of unveiling
        my power</JESUS>  <JESUS>has not yet come.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 2:4
        content: "  Or literally \u201CWoman, what is that for you and for me?\u201D
          This is an Aramaic idiom meaning, \u201CWhat do we have in common if I
          do this?\u201D For Mary, it would change very little, but for Jesus, this
          would be his first public miracle and would dramatically change his ministry
          from that moment on because the crowds would see the power that he possessed.
          Jesus knew his miracle ministry would \u201Ccome out of hiding\u201D by
          performing a miracle. Yet with Mary\u2019s encouragement, Jesus proceeded
          to do just that.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Mary then went to the servers and told them, \u201CWhatever Jesus
        tells you, do it!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Nearby stood six stone water pots [[COMMENT(0)]] meant to be used
        for the Jewish washing rituals.  Each one could hold about twenty gallons
        or more. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:6
        content: "  Six is the number for man, for man was made on the sixth day.
          These six stone jars could represent man\u2019s method of helping others.
          It is nothing but water. But Jesus changes the water of the Word of God
          into the wine of the Spirit. True spiritual life can fill our vessel as
          we bring joy to the world. The fruit of the Spirit includes joy, and there
          is no limit to the joy available for the child of God. See  .      This
          was an outward purification (baptism) for worshipers coming into a synagogue.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Jesus came to the servers and instructed them, <JESUS>\u201CFill
        the</JESUS>  <JESUS>pots with water, right up to the very brim.</JESUS><JESUS>\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Then he said, <JESUS>\u201CNow fill your pitchers and take them to
        the master of ceremonies.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "And when they poured out their pitchers for the master of ceremonies
        to sample, the water had become wine! When he tasted the water that had become
        wine, the master of ceremonies was impressed with its quality. (Although
        he didn\u2019t know where the wine had come from, only the servers knew.)
        He called the bridegroom over "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "and said to him, \u201CEvery host serves his best wine first, until
        everyone has had a cup or two, then he serves the cheaper wine. But you,
        my friend, you\u2019ve reserved the most exquisite wine until now!\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:10
        content: "  Jesus delights in your joy more than you know. He does not withhold
          joy from his people. He created between 120 and 150 gallons of the very
          best wine for a wedding feast! This was one of five miracles that are unique
          to John\u2019s Gospel. The other four are: healing the rich man\u2019s
          son (), healing the crippled man at Bethesda (), healing the blind man
          (), and raising Lazarus from the dead ().    "
    - name: '11: Jesus at the Temple'
      title: Jesus at the Temple
      number: 11
      content: 'This miracle in Cana was the first of the many extraordinary miracles
        Jesus performed in Galilee that revealed his glory, [[COMMENT(0)]] and his
        disciples believed in him. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:11
        content: "  Chapters    could rightly be called \u201CThe Book of Signs,\u201D
          and chs.    \u201CThe Book of Glories.\u201D      Or \u201CThe disciples
          made known his glory and believed in him.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'After the wedding, Jesus, his mother and brothers, and his disciples
        traveled to Capernaum [[COMMENT(0)]] and stayed there for a few days. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:12
        content: "  Capernaum means \u201Cthe village of Nahum\u201D which in turn
          means \u201Cthe village of the comforted.\u201D Jesus did many miracles
          and made his Galilean base of ministry in \u201Cthe village of the comforted.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'When the time was close for the Jewish Passover to begin, Jesus walked
        to Jerusalem. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 2:13
        content: '  From Capernaum to Jerusalem was a journey of nearly one hundred
          miles.    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'As he went into the temple courtyard, he noticed it was filled with
        merchants selling oxen, lambs, and doves for exorbitant prices, while others
        were overcharging as they exchanged currency [[COMMENT(0)]] behind their
        counters. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:14
        content: '  These money changers would exchange Roman currency into Jewish
          currency to pay the temple tax. The leadership of the temple considered
          the Roman currency to be unclean, so the money changers had a captive audience.    '
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'So Jesus found some cords and made them into a whip. Then he drove
        out every one of them and their animals from the courtyard of the temple,
        and he kicked over their tables filled with money, scattering it everywhere!
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 2:15
        content: '  Jesus came to sacrifice his life, which would end animal sacrifices
          and the financial tyranny of religion.    '
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "And he told the merchants, [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>\u201CGet these
        things out of here! Don\u2019t you dare commercialize my Father\u2019s house!\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:16
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe dove dealers.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "That\u2019s when his disciples remembered the Scripture: \u201CI
        am consumed with a fiery passion to keep your house pure!\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:17
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then the Jewish religious leaders challenged Jesus, \u201CWhat authority
        do you have to do this sort of thing and what supernatural sign will you
        show us to prove it?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Jesus answered, <JESUS>\u201CDestroy this temple,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>and I will raise it up again in three days.\u201D</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 2:19
        content: "  Or \u201Csanctuary.\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "Then the Jewish leaders sneered at Jesus\u2019 answer, \u201CThis
        temple took forty-six years [[COMMENT(0)]] to build, and you mean to tell
        us that you will raise it up in three days?\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 2:20
        content: '  Our bodies (temples) have forty-six chromosomes in every cell.    '
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "But they failed to understand that Jesus was speaking of the \u201Ctemple\u201D
        of his body. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:21
        content: "  Resurrection power would be the sign of his supreme authority.
          Jesus\u2019 death and resurrection effectively dismantled the need for
          the temple, for now his powerful gospel of the kingdom realm has built
          us into a holy temple not made with hands. See  ;  ;  . Jesus\u2019 symbolic
          form of speaking was so different than the teachings of the Pharisees,
          as it is to the understanding of many Christians today. The God who was
          once worshiped by animal sacrifices is now to be worshiped in spirit and
          truth, and every believer serves as a priest.  "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: The disciples remembered his prophecy after Jesus rose from the dead,
        and believed both the Scripture and what Jesus had said.
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'While Jesus was at the Passover Feast, the number of his followers
        began to grow, and many gave their allegiance to him because of all the miraculous
        signs they had seen him doing! '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'But Jesus did not yet entrust himself to them, because he knew how
        fickle human hearts can be. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: He needed no one to tell him about human nature, for he fully understood
        what man was capable of doing.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Nicodemus'
      title: Nicodemus
      number: 1
      content: 'Now there was a prominent religious leader among the Jews named Nicodemus,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] who was part of the sect called the Pharisees. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:1
        content: "  Nicodemus means \u201Cconqueror.\u201D Here we see a distinguished
          and moral man speaking with Jesus. In the next chapter, we will see an
          immoral woman coming to know Jesus, the woman at Jacob\u2019s well.    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "One night he discreetly came to Jesus and said, \u201CRabbi, we know
        that you are a teacher come from God, for no one performs the miracle signs
        that you do, unless God\u2019s power is with him.\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Jesus answered, <JESUS>\u201CNicodemus, listen to this eternal truth:
        Before a person can even perceive God\u2019s kingdom, they must first experience
        a rebirth.\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 3:3
        content: "  The Greek word can be translated \u201Cborn from above.\u201D
          However, in the context Nicodemus understood it as a rebirth. The Aramaic
          word is clearly \u201Cborn from the origin.\u201D Nicodemus came seeking
          knowledge; Jesus offered him life.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Nicodemus said, \u201CRebirth? How can a gray-headed man be reborn?
        It\u2019s impossible for anyone to go back into the womb a second time and
        be reborn!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Jesus answered, <JESUS>\u201CI speak an eternal truth: Unless you
        are born of water</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>and the Spirit, you will
        never enter God\u2019s kingdom.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:5
        content: "  The pure water of the Word of God cleanses us and gives us life.
          See  ;  ;  . Some see in the water and Spirit analogy the creative beginning
          of  , where God\u2019s life-giving Spirit fluttered over the chaotic waters.
          New creation life comes the same way. Water and blood gushed from the side
          of our Lord Jesus. He was the last Adam who gave birth to his bride from
          his pierced side.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: <JESUS>For the natural realm only gives birth to things that are natural,
        but the spiritual realm gives birth to supernatural life!</JESUS>
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CYou shouldn\u2019t be amazed by my statement,</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>\u2018You all must be born from above!\u2019</JESUS>    "
      comments:
      - number: 3:7
        content: "  Or \u201Csay to you all.\u201D      A common poetic form of Hebraic
          teaching is to use a play on words, which Jesus utilizes in this poetic
          masterpiece with multiple words containing dual meanings. The word for
          \u201Creborn\u201D can also be translated \u201Cborn from above.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "<JESUS>For the Spirit-Wind blows as it chooses. You can hear its
        sound,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>but you don\u2019t know where it came
        from or where it\u2019s going. So it is the same with those who are Spirit-born!\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:8
        content: "  The word for \u201Cblow\u201D can also be translated \u201Cbreathe.\u201D
          The word for \u201Csound\u201D can be translated \u201Cvoice.\u201D And
          the same word for \u201CSpirit\u201D can also mean \u201Cwind.\u201D If
          our new birth is so mysterious, how much more will be the ways of living
          each moment by the movement of the Holy Spirit? One can understand how
          confused Nicodemus was, for he took everything at face value and couldn\u2019t
          see a deeper meaning.      Or \u201CThe Spirit moves you as he chooses,
          and you hear his voice, but you don\u2019t know where he came from or where
          he goes.\u201D The Aramaic is so rich and multilayered in this passage.
          Perhaps it could be paraphrased as \u201CThe wind, the breath, and the
          Spirit are moved by mysterious moods and in their own wonderful ways. When
          you feel their touch and hear their voices, you know they are real, but
          you don\u2019t understand how they flow and move over the earth. The same
          mysterious way is the way of everyone born by wind, breath, and Spirit.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Nicodemus replied, \u201CI don\u2019t understand; what do you mean?
        How does this happen?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Jesus answered, <JESUS>\u201CNicodemus, aren\u2019t you the respected
        teacher in Israel, and yet you don\u2019t understand this revelation?</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "<JESUS>I speak eternal truths about things I know, things I\u2019ve
        seen and experienced\u2014and still you don\u2019t accept what I reveal.</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "<JESUS>If you\u2019re unable to believe what I\u2019ve told you about
        the natural realm, what will you do when I begin to unveil the heavenly realm?</JESUS>  "
      comments: []
    - name: "13: God\u2019s Love for Everyone"
      title: "God\u2019s Love for Everyone"
      number: 13
      content: "<JESUS>No one has risen into the heavenly realm except the Son of
        Man who also exists in heaven.\u201D</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 3:13
        content: "  Jesus shared a mystery with Nicodemus. While he was on the earth
          ministering, Jesus was also in heaven in the spirit realm. Being in two
          places at the same time is also the privilege given to every believer.
          We are at the same time seated with Christ in the heavenly realm, but also
          living our life on earth to please him. This is what it means to be \u201Cin
          Christ.\u201D See  ;  . In the realm of the Spirit, heaven and earth are
          one. Jesus was telling Nicodemus that only those who are seated in the
          heavenly realm will understand spiritual truths. See  . Most Greek manuscripts
          read \u201Cthe Son of Man who came from heaven.\u201D But the Aramaic is
          clearly \u201Cwho is in heaven.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CAnd just as Moses in the desert lifted up the brass
        replica of a venomous snake on a pole</JESUS>  <JESUS>for all the people
        to see and be healed,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>so the Son of Man is
        ready to be lifted up,</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:14
        content: "  See  . The brass snake symbolizes sin and disease. The Hebrew
          uses a word,  , which means a fiery one (fiery serpent). All of humanity
          has been bitten by the \u201Csnake of sin,\u201D but Jesus was raised up
          on a cross for all people to see. We only need to look to him and believe,
          and we are healed and saved from sin.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: '<JESUS>so that those who truly believe in him</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>will not perish but be given eternal life.</JESUS>  '
      comments:
      - number: 3:15
        content: "  The Aramaic participle can also be \u201Cbelieve on him\u201D
          or \u201Cbelieve into him,\u201D which could explain the variations found
          in the Greek text.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "<JESUS>For here is the way God loved the world\u2014he gave his only,
        unique Son</JESUS>  <JESUS>as a gift.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>So
        now everyone who believes in him</JESUS>    <JESUS>will never perish but
        experience everlasting life.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 3:16
        content: "  Or \u201CGod proved he loved the world by giving his Son.\u201D     
          Or \u201Cbelieve into him.\u201D Salvation and regeneration come only by
          faith. True faith (Gr.  ) contains a number of components: acceptance,
          embracing something (someone) as truth, union with God and his Word, and
          an inner confidence that God alone is enough.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "<JESUS>\u201CGod did not send his Son into the world to judge and
        condemn the world, but to be its Savior and rescue it!</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:17
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201Cso that they shall live by his hand\u201D
          (of power).    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: '<JESUS>So now there is no longer any condemnation for those who believe
        in him, but the unbeliever already lives under condemnation because they
        do not believe in the name of the only Son of God.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 3:18
        content: "  Or \u201Cone and only Son.\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: '<JESUS>And here is the basis for their judgment: The Light</JESUS> 
        <JESUS>of God</JESUS>  <JESUS>has now come into the world, but the people
        loved darkness more than the Light, because they want the darkness to conceal
        their evil.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: '<JESUS>So the wicked hate the Light and try to hide from it, for
        the Light fully exposes their lives.</JESUS>  '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: John, Friend of the Bridegroom'
      title: John, Friend of the Bridegroom
      number: 21
      content: "<JESUS>But those who love the truth</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>will
        come into the Light, for the Light will reveal that it was God who produced
        their fruitful works.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:21
        content: "  Or \u201Cpractice the truth.\u201D      Some scholars believe
          that vv.    are explanatory material supplied by John, the author, rather
          than the words of Jesus.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Then Jesus and his disciples left for a length of time into the Judean
        countryside where they baptized the people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'At this time John was still baptizing people at Aenon, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        near Salim,  where there was plenty of water, and the people kept coming
        for John to baptize them. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:23
        content: "  The Aramaic location is  , which in Aramaic means \u201Cthe spring
          of doves,\u201D or \u201Cdove\u2019s eyes.\u201D The Greek manuscripts
          have transliterated this to  .      Or in Aramaic,  , which means \u201Cto
          follow.\u201D One ancient tradition refers to this location to be eight
          miles south of the town of Scythopolis, or  .    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: (This was before John was thrown into prison.)
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "An argument started between John\u2019s disciples and a particular
        Jewish man about baptism. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:25
        content: "  Or \u201Cpurification.\u201D The implication is that the Jewish
          man was telling John\u2019s disciples that Jesus\u2019 baptism was better
          than John\u2019s.    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "So they went to John and asked him, \u201CTeacher, are you aware
        that the One you told us about at the crossing place\u2014he\u2019s now baptizing
        crowds larger than yours. People are flocking to him!\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "John answered them, \u201CA person cannot receive even one thing
        unless God bestows it. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:27
        content: "  Or \u201CNo one of his own will can receive anything unless it
          comes to him from heaven.\u201D    "
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "You\u2019ve heard me tell you that I am not the Messiah, but certainly
        I am the messenger sent ahead of him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "He is the Bridegroom, [[COMMENT(0)]] and the bride belongs to him.
        I am the friend  of the Bridegroom who stands nearby and listens with great
        joy to the Bridegroom\u2019s voice. Because of his words, my joy is complete
        and overflows! "
      comments:
      - number: 3:29
        content: "  See  ;  .      Or \u201Cfamily member.\u201D    "
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'It is necessary for him to increase [[COMMENT(0)]] and for me to
        decrease. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:30
        content: "  The increase of Christ in v.    is the bride of Christ in v. 
          . We are the increase of Christ as his counterpart. Just as Eve was the
          increase of Adam, the bride is the increase of Christ on the earth.     
          Or \u201CHe is destined to become greater, and I must be pruned.\u201D
          Some translations end John the Baptizer\u2019s words here and make vv.   
          the words of John the apostle.    "
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201CFor the one who is from the earth belongs to the earth and
        speaks from the natural realm. But the One who comes from above is above
        everything and speaks of the highest realm of all! "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "His message is about what he has seen and experienced, even though
        people don\u2019t accept it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "Yet those who embrace his message know in their hearts that it\u2019s
        the truth. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 3:33
        content: "  The Aramaic is \u201CThose who accept his testimony take God\u2019s
          true seal (upon them).\u201D    "
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201CThe One whom God has sent to represent him will speak the words
        of God, because God has poured out upon him the fullness of the Holy Spirit
        without limitation. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 3:34
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe Spirit does not give anything in small measures.\u201D
          There is some textual evidence that this verse is saying, \u201CThe Son
          gives the Spirit [to his people] without measure.\u201D    "
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'The Father loves his Son so much that he has given all things into
        his hands. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 3:35
        content: "  The text is simply \u201Che has given all into his hands.\u201D
          The \u201Call\u201D can be all things, or \u201Call authority,\u201D but
          can also mean \u201Call people.\u201D    "
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "Those who trust in the Son possess eternal life; those who don\u2019t
        obey [[COMMENT(0)]] the Son will not see life, and God\u2019s anger will
        rise up against them.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 3:36
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201Cthose who do not cling to
          the Son.\u201D      As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cwrath
          rests upon them.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: A Thirsty Savior'
      title: A Thirsty Savior
      number: 1
      content: 'The news quickly reached the Jewish religious leaders known as the
        Pharisees that Jesus was drawing greater crowds of followers coming to be
        baptized than John. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "(Although Jesus himself didn\u2019t baptize, but only his disciples.) "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Jesus  [[COMMENT(0)]] heard what was being said and abruptly left
        Judea and returned to the province of Galilee, '
      comments:
      - number: 4:3
        content: "  Some manuscripts have \u201CThe Lord.\u201D This is included
          here from v.    for the sake of the English narrative.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: and he had to pass through Samaria. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 4:4
        content: '  Since the Jews despised the Samaritans, they often traveled east
          of the Jordan River to avoid Samaria while traveling between Judaea and
          Galilee. The Jews wanted nothing to do with the Samaritans because they
          had mixed Jewish and gentile blood and centered their worship at Mount
          Gerizim instead of Jerusalem. The Lord Jesus needed to pass through Samaria
          because there were needy souls who needed a Savior.    '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Jesus arrived at the Samaritan village of Sychar, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        near the field that Jacob had given to his son Joseph. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:5
        content: '  Sychar lies near modern-day Nablus in the northern region of
          the West Bank. A village named Askar, which was formerly known as Sychar,
          lies about one kilometer north of the well.    '
    - name: '6-8: '
      title: 
      number: 6-8
      content: "Wearied by his long journey, he sat on the edge of Jacob\u2019s well,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and sent his disciples into the village to buy food, for it
        was already afternoon.Soon a Samaritan woman came to draw water. Jesus said
        to her, <JESUS>\u201CGive me a drink.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: "4:6\u20138"
        content: "  Jacob\u2019s well was \u201Ca spring-fed well.\u201D This well
          becomes a picture of the \u201Cspring\u201D of the Jacob-life inside of
          every one of us. Fed by Adam\u2019s fall, this spring has flowed through
          all of humanity. But Jesus sat as a \u201Clid\u201D to Jacob\u2019s well,
          sealing its polluted stream. In Christ, Jacob\u2019s clever striving has
          ended. A living well became a lid to Jacob\u2019s well as Jesus sat there
          ready to give his living water to all who would come and drink. A well
          sat upon a well.      The \u201Cwater\u201D Jesus wanted was the refreshing,
          satisfying pleasure of her devotion. He says to each one of us, \u201CNothing
          satisfies me except you.\u201D When the sinner drank of the Savior and
          the Savior drank of the sinner, both were satisfied. Neither ate or drank,
          but each satisfied the other.    "
    - name: '6-8: '
      title: 
      number: 6-8
      content: "Wearied by his long journey, he sat on the edge of Jacob\u2019s well,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] and sent his disciples into the village to buy food, for it
        was already afternoon.Soon a Samaritan woman came to draw water. Jesus said
        to her, <JESUS>\u201CGive me a drink.\u201D</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: "4:6\u20138"
        content: "  Jacob\u2019s well was \u201Ca spring-fed well.\u201D This well
          becomes a picture of the \u201Cspring\u201D of the Jacob-life inside of
          every one of us. Fed by Adam\u2019s fall, this spring has flowed through
          all of humanity. But Jesus sat as a \u201Clid\u201D to Jacob\u2019s well,
